# Matrix Multiplication Performance Study

## From Loop Order to Memory Bandwidth Limits

---

# Goal of This Experiment

I originally wanted to answer a very simple question:

> Does changing the order of loops actually matter?

I expected small differences.

Instead, this experiment took me through:

* Cache locality,
* Loop ordering,
* Matrix scaling,
* Blocking,
* Multithreading,
* Memory bandwidth saturation.

I eventually discovered that moving data is often more expensive than doing the actual computations.

---

# The Problem

Suppose we want to multiply two square matrices:

Matrix A × Matrix B = Matrix C

If each matrix has:

N rows and N columns,

then every element of Matrix C is calculated by:

* taking one row from Matrix A,
* taking one column from Matrix B,
* multiplying corresponding elements,
* adding all of them together.

---

# How Much Computation Is Actually Happening?

For an N × N matrix multiplication:

There are:

N × N elements in Matrix C.

Each element requires:

* N multiplications,
* N additions.

So total work is approximately:

Total Operations

= 2 × N³

---

For my largest experiment:

N = 4096

Therefore:

Total Operations

= 2 × 4096³

= 137,438,953,472 operations

≈ 137.44 billion operations

≈ 137.44 GFLOPs of work.

This means:

> Even though the code looks simple, the processor is actually doing over 137 billion mathematical operations.

---

# Phase 1: Loop Ordering

I tested six loop orders.

IJK

IKJ

JIK

JKI

KIJ

KJI

using:

N = 512

---

# Results

| Loop Order | Execution Time |
| ---------- | -------------: |
| IJK        |        0.232 s |
| IKJ        |        0.143 s |
| JIK        |        0.228 s |
| JKI        |        0.238 s |
| KIJ        |        0.150 s |
| KJI        |        0.235 s |

---

# What Surprised Me?

The fastest version:

IKJ

was roughly

1.6× faster

than some of the slowest versions.

The algorithm was exactly the same.

The mathematics was exactly the same.

Only the order of the loops changed.

---

# Why Did This Happen?

Because the CPU does not read directly from RAM every time.

Instead it uses:

L1 Cache

↓

L2 Cache

↓

L3 Cache

↓

RAM

The closer the memory is to the CPU:

* the smaller it is,
* the faster it is.

---

# What Makes IKJ Fast?

In C, rows are stored continuously.

For example:

A[0][0], A[0][1], A[0][2] ...

are adjacent in memory.

IKJ walks through memory in this order.

That means:

* cache lines are reused,
* fewer cache misses occur,
* the CPU spends more time computing.

---

# Important Observation

I noticed something interesting:

> The variable closest to the actual computation affected performance the most.

If the innermost loop walked through memory sequentially:

the program became fast.

If it jumped around memory:

the CPU stalled.

This taught me:

> The order of loops determines whether the processor computes or waits.

---

# Phase 2: Scaling Matrix Size

I then kept the best loop order and increased matrix size.

---

# Results

| Matrix Size | Execution Time |
| ----------: | -------------: |
|     32 × 32 |     0.000174 s |
|     64 × 64 |     0.000960 s |
|   128 × 128 |     0.006724 s |
|   256 × 256 |     0.038270 s |
|   512 × 512 |     0.176229 s |
| 1024 × 1024 |     1.231725 s |
| 2048 × 2048 |     9.770896 s |
| 4096 × 4096 |    79.413116 s |

---

# What Happened?

Execution time exploded.

At first I thought:

"This is just because matrix multiplication is O(N³)."

But that wasn't the whole story.

As matrices became larger:

they stopped fitting inside cache.

The CPU had to fetch data from slower memory more often.

---

# What I Learned

Performance depends on two things:

1. Computation

How much arithmetic is required.

2. Data Movement

How much information must travel through the memory hierarchy.

As matrices grow:

data movement becomes increasingly important.

---

# Phase 3: Blocking

I then divided the matrices into smaller chunks.

Instead of processing the whole matrix at once,

I processed smaller tiles.

The idea was:

> Keep smaller working sets inside cache.

---

# Blocking Results

| Block Size | Execution Time |
| ---------: | -------------: |
|          4 |       113.67 s |
|          8 |       101.90 s |
|         16 |        92.68 s |
|         32 |        86.96 s |
|         64 |        85.04 s |
|        128 |        84.80 s |

---

# Observation

Blocking helped,

but not dramatically.

Larger blocks performed better.

However,

even the best blocked version was still slow.

Why?

Because the matrices were simply too large.

RAM accesses still dominated.

---

# Phase 4: Multithreading

I then divided the work among multiple threads.

Each thread computed different rows of Matrix C.

Since threads wrote to separate rows,

no synchronization was needed.

---

# Results

| Threads | Block Size | Execution Time |
| ------: | ---------: | -------------: |
|       1 |        128 |        84.80 s |
|       8 |        128 |        11.39 s |
|      16 |        128 |         8.04 s |
|      32 |        128 |         8.04 s |
|      64 |        128 |         8.10 s |

---

# Speedup

8 threads:

84.80 ÷ 11.39

≈ 7.44× faster

---

16 threads:

84.80 ÷ 8.04

≈ 10.55× faster

---

# Actual Performance

Using:

137.44 GFLOPs of total work,

I calculated:

Single thread:

≈ 1.62 GFLOPS

8 threads:

≈ 12.06 GFLOPS

16 threads:

≈ 17.09 GFLOPS

---

# Then Something Strange Happened

I expected:

More Threads

↓

More Speed

But this stopped happening.

16 threads:

8.04 s

32 threads:

8.04 s

64 threads:

8.10 s

Nothing improved.

---

# Why?

I had reached the machine's limit.

The bottleneck shifted.

Before:

The CPU lacked enough arithmetic power.

Now:

The CPU had enough arithmetic power,

but could not obtain data quickly enough.

RAM became the limiting factor.

---

# Memory Bandwidth Saturation

This phenomenon is called:

Memory Bandwidth Saturation.

It means:

> The processor spends more time waiting for data than performing calculations.

At this point:

Adding more threads does not help.

The memory subsystem becomes the bottleneck.

---

# The Biggest Lesson

I started with:

"Does loop order matter?"

I ended up discovering:

Loop Order

↓

Cache Locality

↓

Matrix Scaling

↓

Blocking

↓

Multithreading

↓

Memory Bandwidth Saturation

---

# Final Conclusion

This experiment taught me one of the most important lessons in High Performance Computing:

> Modern processors are incredibly fast at arithmetic.

The real challenge is getting the right data to the processor at the right time.

In many cases,

moving data is more expensive than computing on it.

Understanding how memory behaves is therefore just as important as understanding algorithms themselves.
